Thus, the depth is approximately 597 micrometers. **Final Answer** The depth at which the concentration of helium is reduced to \( \frac{1}{3} \) of its initial value after 10 minutes is \boxed{597} micrometers. </think> To determine the depth at which the concentration of helium decreases to \( \frac{1}{3} \) of its initial value after 10 minutes in a vacuum furnace at \( 400^\circ \mathrm{C} \), we use the solution for semi-infinite diffusion with surface concentration maintained at zero. The relevant formula is: \[ C(x, t) = C_0 \cdot \text{erfc}\left( \frac{x}{2 \sqrt{D t}} \right) \] where \( C(x, t) \) is the concentration at depth \( x \) and time \( t \), \( C_0 \) is the initial concentration, \( D \) is the diffusion coefficient, and \( \text{erfc} \) is the complementary error function. 1. **Convert the diffusion coefficient to cm²/s**: \[ D = 3.091 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{cm}^2/\text{s} \] 2. **Convert time from minutes to seconds**: \[ t = 10 \, \text{minutes} = 600 \, \text{seconds} \] 3. **Calculate \( D \cdot t \)**: \[ D \cdot t = 3.091 \times 10^{-6} \, \text{cm}^2/\text{s} \times 600 \, \text{s} = 1.8546 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{cm}^2 \] 4. **Compute the square root of \( D \cdot t \)**: \[ \sqrt{D \cdot t} = \sqrt{1.8546 \times 10^{-3}} \approx 0.04307 \, \text{cm} \] 5. **Determine the inverse complementary error function value**: \[ \text{erfc}^{-1}\left( \frac{1}{3} \right) \approx 0.6929 \] 6. **Calculate the depth \( x \)**: \[ x = 2 \cdot 0.6929 \cdot \sqrt{D \cdot t} \approx 2 \cdot 0.6929 \cdot 0.04307 \approx 0.0597 \, \text{cm} \] 7. **Convert the depth from cm to micrometers**: \[ 0.0597 \, \text{cm} \times 10,000 \, \text{micrometers/cm} = 597 \, \text{micrometers} \] Thus, the depth at which the concentration of helium is reduced to \( \frac{1}{3} \) of its initial value after 10 minutes is \(\boxed{597}\) micrometers.
